solution.p:
We need the radial distance r from the origin to the point:

	r^2 = 4^2 + (-1)^2 = 16 + 1 = 17 \Rightarrow r = \sqrt{17}.

We can now form all the ratios we want with x=4, y = -1, and r = \sqrt{17}





		\sin \theta = \frac{-1}{\sqrt{17}}= -\frac{\sqrt{17}}{17} 
		\csc \theta = \frac{\sqrt{17}}{-1} = - \sqrt{17}



		\cos \theta = \frac{4}{\sqrt{17}}=\frac{4\sqrt{17}}{17} 
		\sec \theta = \frac{\sqrt{17}}{4}



		\tan \theta = -\frac{1}{4}
		\cot \theta = \frac{4}{-1}=-4

Suppose (x,y) is a point in the terminal ray of \theta. Here's what we know:


x \lt 0 is negative;

y \lt 0 is negative;

\tan \theta = \frac{y}{x} = 3.

		So if x = -1 (negative), then y = 3 x = -3. The point (x,y) = (-1,-3) will do. (There are many other options!) The radial distance is

			r^2 = (-1)^2 + (-3)^2 = 1 + 9 = 10 \Rightarrow r = \sqrt{10}.

		So,

			\sin \theta = y/r = -3/\sqrt{10} = -\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{10}

		and

			\cos \theta = x/r = -1/\sqrt{10} = -\frac{\sqrt{10}}{10}.

Suppose (x,y) is a point in the terminal ray of \theta. Here's what we know:


x \lt 0 is negative;

y \lt 0 is negative;

\sin \theta = \frac{y}{r} = -1/3.

		So if y = -1 (negative), then r = 3. The x-coordinate must satisfy

			r^2 = x^2 + y^2 \Rightarrow x^2 = 3^2 - (-1)^2 = 8 \Rightarrow x = \pm \sqrt{8}

		and since x must be negative, we choose x=-\sqrt{8}. The point (-\sqrt{8},-1) is on the terminal ray of our angle. (There are many other options!)
		So,

			\cos \theta = x/r = -\sqrt{8}/3

		and

			\tan \theta = y/x = \frac{-1}{-\sqrt{8}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{8}} = \frac{\sqrt{8}}{8}

ol.li:
 \theta = 150^\circ is in Quadrant II and has reference angle \bar\theta = 30^\circ.







						\sin \theta = +\sin 30^\circ = \frac{1}{2}
						\csc \theta = 2



						\cos \theta = -\cos 30^\circ = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
						\sec \theta = -\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} = - \frac{2\sqrt{3}}{3}



						\tan \theta = -\tan 30^\circ = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}
						\cot \theta = - \sqrt{3}

\theta = -2\pi/3 is in Quadrant III and has reference angle \bar\theta = \pi/3.







						\sin \theta = -\sin \pi/3 = -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
						\csc \theta = -\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} = - \frac{2\sqrt{3}}{3}



						\cos \theta = -\cos \pi/3 = -\frac{1}{2}
						\sec \theta = -2



						\tan \theta = +\tan \pi/3 = \sqrt{3}
						\cot \theta =  \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}

\theta = 7\pi/4 is in Quadrant IV and has reference angle \bar\theta = \pi/4.







					\sin \theta = -\sin \pi/4 = -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
					\csc \theta = -\frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} = - \frac{2\sqrt{2}}{2} = - \sqrt{2}



					\cos \theta = +\cos \pi/4 = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
					\sec \theta = \sqrt{2}



					\tan \theta = -\tan \pi/4 = -1
					\cot \theta =  -1

\theta = -11\pi/4 is in Quadrant III and has reference angle \bar\theta = \pi/4.







					\sin \theta = -\sin \pi/4 =- \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
					\csc \theta = -\sqrt{2}



					\cos \theta = -\cos \pi/4 = -\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
					\sec \theta = -\sqrt{2}



					\tan \theta = +\tan \pi/4 = 1
					\cot \theta =  1

solution.p:
Recall that \csc\theta = \frac{1}{\sin\theta}. Think about what this means:


When sine is small (close to zero), cosecant will be large;

When sine is zero, cosecant will be undefined (vertical asymptote);

When sine is negative, cosecant will be negative.

statement.p:
Use the the appropriate identities to simplify the following expression as much as possible.

		\frac{\tan \theta \, \csc^3 \theta}{\cot^4 \theta \, \sin^5 \theta\, (1-\sin^2 \theta)}

	Your final answer should not include any ratios.
